When a small group of living creatures (one small population) gets to be isolated from the main population from which they come (for example, if they move over a mountain range or river or if they move to a new island, from where they cannot return easily), they will often find themselves in an environment different from the one in which they have been before.
This new environment has different resources and different competitors, so the new population will need different features or adaptations to be a more powerful competitor than what they needed before.
The original population has not changed at all, it needs the same adaptations as before.
As time goes of the new population adapting to the environment, its members begin to look less and less like the other populations.
Finally, after thousands or even millions of years, the two populations will look so different from each other that we will not be able to say that they are the same species.
This process bears the name of specialization, which means the formation of new species. The specialization is a consequence that can not be avoided and is a very important part of the evolution.
